agency_name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)
request_text: Dear Sir or Madam, This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act. 5 U.S.C. §552, et seq. I request that a copy of the following documents [or documents containing the following information] be provided to me: [A copy of firearm mortality rates / gun violence deaths in the U.S. sorted by date, year, state, age, sex, race and ethnicity issued between 2018 and 2022]. As you know, FOIA requires agencies to release information unless it is specifically exempt from disclosure, and also requires agencies to release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of documents, i.e., to redact exempt portions of documents and release the rest. See 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(8). In order to help to determine my status for purposes of determining the applicability of any fees, you should know that I am a student reporter at California State University Long Beach and this request is made as part of scholarly research and for possible news gathering and not for a commercial use. I request a waiver of all fees for this request. Disclosure of the requested information to me is in the public interest because it is likely to contribute significantly to public understanding of the operations or activities of the government and is not in my commercial interest. I request that the information I seek be provided in electronic format, either as a .csv file or an .xls file. I also include a telephone number at which I can be contacted during the hours of 2 to 5pm, if necessary, to discuss any aspect of my request. I have also included my email address. Thank you for your prompt consideration of this request. Sincerely, Valerie Alba (Date Range for Record Search: From 01/01/2018 To 12/31/2022)

agency_name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)
request_text: 1) A full report of the number of passengers and staff members who tested positive for COVID-19 on cruise ship Regatta that departed Papeete, Tahiti on April 6, 2022. 2) A full report on the number of positive tested COVID passengers, including names and addresses, that were debarked from the Regatta on April 23, 2022 at the port in Long Beach, CA, and were transported to the Hotel Maya, in Long Beach, CA. 3) Evidence of compliance and a copy of the full report for the Regatta as required by U.S. Regulation 42 CFR 71, as stated below: “U.S. regulations (42 CFR 71) require the master of a ship destined for a U.S. port of entry to immediately report any death or illness among the ship’s passengers or crew. This includes persons who have been disembarked or have been removed from the ship due to illness or death.” “Reports must immediately be made to the CDC Quarantine Station at or nearest the U.S. port of arrival. For ships arriving in the United States, this includes all deaths or illnesses that occurred within 15 days prior to arrival.” 4) Evidence that the COVID-19 disembarked passengers were medically transported to the hotel. 5) Evidence that upon learning about the COVID-19 outbreak, cruise line officials did everything possible to mitigate the problem, such as making announcements of the outbreak, requiring masks, practicing social distancing, and stressing the need to follow other protocols. 6) Evidence that all other (regularly debarking passengers) were tested for COVID-19 prior to debarkation. 7) A full report of the number of passengers that tested positive on the next cruise on the Regatta. 8) Evidence that the ship was fully sanitized before departing in its next cruise. 9) And regarding the crew, provide evidence that: a) Crew shore leaves were cancelled, b) Self-serving dining options were eliminated, c) A “working quarantine” was implemented, and d) the HVAC system was adjusted to maximize outdoor air.

request_text: All information and communications from/to/between/among Charity Rychak Delaney (P.E. Environmental Engineer, Camp Lejeune) and S. Williams (electronic communication, February 4, 2015) and CDC/ATSDR associated with the preparation of the document “Public Health assessment for Camp Lejeune Drinking Water, U.S. Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, January 20, 2017”, specifically materials that Charity Rychak Delaney and S. Williams provided ATSDR responding to and addressing questions from ATSDR about Camp Lejeune, including the following: 1. The temperature of the indoor swimming pool water (assumed to be 80 degrees Fahrenheit). C. Delaney, electronic communication, August 18, 2014 Page 109, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 2. The frequency of basic and intermediate training in the indoor pool (i.e., basic training occurred 1 day per year, advanced training occurred 5 days per year, and pre-dive training occurred an additional 14 days per year). C. Delaney, electronic communication, August 18, 2014 Page 109, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 3. The estimated number of indoor pool training hours for each training level. C. Delaney, electronic communication, August 20, 2014 Page 109, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 4. The dynamics of indoor pool filling with new water, including but not limited to the backwashing schedule (e.g., 8–10 inches every 100 hours). C. Delaney, electronic communication, Dec. 2014 Page 110, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 5. The as-built drawings from which ATSDR determined the number of steam presses and washing machines located inside specific laundry facilities at Camp Lejeune and the calculations used to estimate inhalation exposures from these facilities. C. Delaney, electronic communication, September 16, 2014 Page 112, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 6. Information associated with the determination that before 1986 proper ventilation to collect the steam in the laundry facility rooms was not installed. C. Delaney, electronic communication, July 24, 2014 Page 113, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 7. The approximate dimensions of the mess hall rooms where workers were exposed by prerinsing dishes and operating dishwashers as estimated by Camp Lejeune personnel and given to ATSDR. C. Delaney, electronic communication, July 16, 2014 Page 114, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 8. The floor plans provided by Camp Lejeune personnel from which the dimensions of the room where steam tables were located were determined. S. Williams, electronic communication, February 4, 2015 Page 114, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 9. The calculations used to estimate inhalation exposures from dishwashing and steam table activities in mess hall facilities. Page 115, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 10. Communications reflecting that the calculations used to estimate inhalation exposures from dishwashing and steam table activities in mess hall facilities do not take clean air exchange rates into consideration (i.e., before 1986, no fume hoods existed to collect the steam and it would build up in the mess hall facility rooms). C. Delaney, electronic communication, July 24, 2014 Page 115, ATSDR, PHA, 2017 11. All calculations, including inputs and results not provided in the 2017 ATSDR PHA associated with swimming and occupational exposures and not covered by the above FOIA requests.

agency_name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)
request_text: hereby request from the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) all data that would permit a replication and reanalysis of 1) the Steenland, et al,1,2 ethylene oxide (EtO) cohort mortality and breast cancer incidence studies conducted by NIOSH and 2) the use of these data by EPA in the ethylene oxide IRIS 2016. We request access to the related exposure file and a method for linkage of study subjects to their exposures. We also request codebooks and file layout documentation for the exposure, incidence and mortality data files. These data were used by EPA in conjunction with the ethylene oxide IRIS 2016, the recent 2022 Miscellaneous Organic Chemical Manufacturing (the MON) rule for EtO, and the 2023 hazardous organic NESHAP (HON) proposed rule. Risk assessments that have major impacts such as the MON and HON rules must be transparent so that anyone can evaluate the scientific basis for decision making. Thus, all the NIOSH data should be made available.

request_text: This is a request for records under the Freedom of Information Act (“FOIA”), 5 U.S.C. § 552 and the Privacy Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552a. This request should be considered under both statutes to maximize the release of records. Requester Information Name: Colin Aamot Position: Freelance Investigative Journalist Address: (b)(6) Email: (b)(6) Phone: (b)(6) Records Sought I request disclosure on the following records: Full FOIA Logs, years 2000-present If responsive records are found please include the all documents, all attachments, and all pertinent records regardless of format. If the agency's position is that records are exempt from disclosure, please provide an index as required under Vaughn v. Rosen 484 F.2d 820 (D.C. Cir. 1973.). Under 5 U.S.C(a)(4)(iii), “Documents shall be furnished without charge…if disclosure of the information is in the public interest because it is likely to contribute significantly to public understanding of the operations or activities of the government and is not primarily in the commercial interest of the requester. “ Disclosure in this case meets the statutory criteria, as the records sought to detail the operations and the activities of the government. The public interest in this significant expansion of public understanding of government operations far outweighs any commercial interest of my own in the requested release. If I am not granted a complete fee waiver, I request to be considered a member of the news media for fee purposes. I am willing to pay all reasonable expenses incurred in the process of the FOIA request. My previous journalistic work has been featured in Muckrock, the Centcom press portal, local publications, among others. Respectfully, Colin Aamot

request_text: Cozen O’Connor hereby submits this request for information pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act (“FOIA”), 5 U.S.C. § 552. Cozen O’Connor seeks the following electronic or hard-copy documents in the possession, custody or control of the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (“CDC”), any division thereof, or any District Office related to the 2021/2022 E. coli O157:H7 outbreak referenced in the January 6, 2022 report (hereinafter, the “Outbreak”), and specifically those records pertaining to Josie’s Organics. Such records may, in the interest of time, be provided to us on a rolling or staggered basis as they are obtained and reviewed: 1. Sample Analysis, Receipt for Samples, microbiological results of any product, water, or environmental sample or sub-sample that (a) were collected by CDC any division thereof, any other federal agency (including, without limitation, the USDA-FSIS and/or FDA), or any state agency, and (b) relate to any inspection or investigation regarding the Outbreak. 2. All documents comprising, relating, or referring to any detailed food histories that (a) were collected by CDC, any division thereof, any other federal agency, or any state agency, and (b) relate to any inspection or investigation regarding the Outbreak. 3. All documents relating or referring to lettuce or baby spinach as a source or potential source of the Outbreak. a. The documents requested in Request 3 include, but are not limited to, documents referring or relating to samples or subsamples collected from any grower, shipper, harvester, supplier, and/or processor of lettuce or baby spinach and any related ingredients related to the subject investigation. 4. All documents relating or referring to Laboratory and Traceback Data regarding the Outbreak. 5. Product codes (production and lot codes) for product that is the basis of the traceback for the referenced Outbreak investigation and all supporting traceback records. 6. All Establishment Inspection Reports for any entity (farms/growers, harvesters, suppliers, shippers, manufacturers) associated with the Outbreak. 7. All investigations and/or inspections associated with capturing any observations of entities associated with the Outbreak. 8. All documents (including data, reports, correspondence, or summaries) relating or referring to testing or health surveillance data collected by any Federal or state agency related to the Outbreak. 9. The CDC Line List concerning the Outbreak and all documents related thereto. (Date Range for Record Search: From 01/01/2018 To 05/16/2023)

request_text: I am requesting copies of all documents and records held by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) relating to any confirmed or suspected illnesses caused by any strain of Shiga toxin-producing Escherichia coli (STEC) in the state of Michigan, between the dates of March 1, 2023, and the present. By way of further limiting the scope of relevant documents and records, I would like to limit my request to the following information: 1. All documents, investigative information or data, reports, memos, or summaries relating to any investigation involving confirmed or suspected STEC cases in the State of Michigan, including any outbreaks or clusters of cases, during the relevant time frame. 2. Any epidemiological studies, assessments, or evaluations conducted by or shared with the CDC regarding known or suspected STEC cases in Michigan during the relevant period. 3. Any communications, correspondence, or other written exchanges between the CDC and 1) the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services; 2) the Kent County Health Department; or, 3) any other state, county, or local health agencies, concerning STEC cases, outbreaks, or related matters during the relevant period. Please include all relevant documents, regardless of format, including but not limited to emails, letters, reports, meeting minutes, presentations, and any other written or electronic records. If you determine that any portion of the requested records is exempt from disclosure under the Freedom of Information Act, I request that you provide me with a written explanation of the basis for each claimed exemption. We will pay any statutory fees related to the preparation and transmittal of the requested isolate and information. If, however, the fees for the preparation and transmittal of the isolate and information will exceed $250.00, please contact me directly for approval. Additionally, in the event this request is denied in whole or in part for any reason, please cite the specific exemption upon which you base any such denial, and inform me of the procedures available to appeal any such decision under the law. Thank you in advance for your expeditious attention to this request. We look forward to your prompt response.

In what part of the Pentagon (including outside, inside, corridor, however you have this if you have it) were they working. If it was interior work, by floor, wedge, or corridor is requested, to the extent available. g. Time period of exposure (however you have it) h. Number receiving workers compensation for the issues. i. Deaths among personnel diagnosed with pulmonary issues, stratified by date ranges After 9-11 (e.g, 1 year, 2 years, etc). j. request_text: An outbreak of E. coli O118/O151: H2 was investigated by the CDC, FDA, and state partners. Specimens from cases affected by this outbreak were isolated from March 2023 to April 2023. Marler Clark Law Firm represents clients who fell ill in this outbreak. We are writing to request copies of any records on file at the CDC, compiled between March 1, 2023 and today, regarding the investigation of this outbreak (CDC ID: 2304MLEXY-1). We specifically request: • summary reports (NORS reports and/or slides) of any investigation done for this outbreak, including the final number of cases and information regarding the suspected source; • a most current linelist of all cases considered a part of the outbreak (CDC ID: 2304MLEXY-1); • any WGS analyses conducted on cases included in the outbreak (phylogenetic trees with WGS IDs); and • any traceback information regarding the sources associated with this outbreak. request_text: Pursuant to the federal Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552 et seq., I am requesting an electronic copy of the ATSDR’s 1996 “Health Consultation” for the “Spelter Zinc Plant” in West Virginia. I am making this request as a journalist and intend to use the information in order to write and publish articles for public dissemination. Thomson Reuters is the largest news agency in the world. Therefore, I request that the CDC/ATSDR recognize Reuters’s news media status and, in light of the public interest in dissemination of financial disclosure analysis, waive any fees associated with responding, including research and duplication. And because I am making this request as a journalist and the information is of timely news value, I would appreciate your communicating with me by telephone or electronic mail, rather than postal mail. Should my request be denied in whole or in part, I ask that the CDC/ATSDR justify all denial or withholding by reference to specific exemptions of the Freedom of Information Act. I also expect CDC/ATSDR to release all segregable portions of otherwise exempt material, and I reserve the right to appeal your decision to withhold any information of deny a fee waiver.

agency_name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)
request_text: June 27, 2023 Re: Hemovigilance Module Incident (57.305) Form, FOIA Dear Sir or Madam: Under the federal Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552 (the “FOIA”), I request as a reporter for National Public Radio, Inc. (NPR) that the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention make available to me for inspection and copying all records of 57.305 forms (Hemovigilance Module Incident) that are required to be reported and submitted through the National Healthcare Safety Network (NHSN) from the state of Massachusetts. Please send all records created January 1, 2014 through the present (till the receipt of this request). If the Patient ID# and Facility ID# can be traced back to the patient and the facility respectively, that information can be redacted before releasing these forms. As you know, the FOIA provides that if portions of a document are exempt from release, the remainder must be segregated and disclosed. Therefore, please send me all non-exempt portions of the records I have requested and justify any deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the FOIA. I reserve the right to appeal your decision to withhold any materials. Since some of the documents listed above may be more readily available than others, please provide the documents that are available as soon as possible without waiting to provide access to all the documents. The FOIA provides for waiver or reduction of fees if disclosure could be considered as “primarily benefiting the general public.” I am a journalist employed by NPR and intend to use the information I am requesting as a basis for a planned news story, which makes me a “representative of the news media.” Therefore, I ask that you waive all duplication fees. If you deny this request, however, and the fees will exceed $25, please notify me of the charges before you fulfill my request so that I may decide whether to pay the fees or appeal your denial of my request for a waiver. I submit this request in my capacity as a journalist, and this information is time-sensitive. Accordingly, I would appreciate your communicating with me by telephone or email at 609-251-7348 or tchristopher@npr.org, rather than by mail, if you have any questions regarding this request. You can also communicate with anyone in NPR’s Legal Department, including Rachel Seller (rseller@npr.org) or Micah Ratner (mratner@npr.org). I look forward to receiving your reply within twenty (20) business days, as required by federal law. Thank you for your anticipated cooperation with this FOIA request. Sincerely, Tirzah Christopher (Date Range for Record Search: From 01/01/2014 To 06/27/2023)

agency_name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)
request_text: Pursuant to the federal Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, I request access to and copies of records from the following FOIA requests, whose case ID’s I have attached. Please see attachment. Part I of the request: Please prioritize requests that have been fulfilled, in which records were produced and/or denied. Please provide an estimated date of completion for this part of my request, as the statute requires. Part II of the request: Please release the records of pending requests to me as those requests are processed and fulfilled. Please contact me if you have any questions about this request. How Responsive Records Should Be Provided I request that copies of the responsive records for this FOIA request be provided in a digital format, either via email, or stored on a CD or other electronic data storage device. See 5 U.S.C. § 552 (a)(3)B). Providing these records in an electronic format will save agency staff processing time, as well as reducing the cost of making paper copies of all responsive records. Background of the Requestor I am professor of international and global history at Columbia University and co-director of its social science research center, the Institute for Social and Economic Research and Policy. I am also the principal investigator of History Lab, a project that uses data science methods to explore contemporary history. My publications include A Diplomatic Revolution: Algeria's Fight for Independence and the Origins of the Post-Cold War Era, Fatal Misconception: The Struggle to Control World Population, and The Declassification Engine: What History Reveals about America’s Top Secrets. Waiver of Duplication and Search Fees We are requesting these records to contribute to building an archive for use by researchers interested in learning lessons from the history of Covid-19. This project is supported by the National Historical Publications and Records Commission, the records will be made available freely to all interested parties at History-Lab.org, and they will be permanently preserved by Columbia University’s Rare Books and Manuscripts Library. The disclosure of the records requested herein will contribute significantly to the understanding of government operations and activities. In particular, the records sought by this FOIA request will help to explain and identify solutions to the problems faced by the U.S. public, elected government officials, and government agencies as they responded to and managed the COVID-19 pandemic. Moreover, I am the principal investigator in a scholarly project, titled “Writing the History of COVID-19: Lessons for the Next Pandemic,” which is housed at Columbia University. Clearly, receipt of the records is not primarily in my commercial interest.
